    <section id="section-1">
      <h2>1. What you need to understand before you start</h2>

      <p>The most common beginner mistake is treating lead generation as a campaign rather than a system. A campaign has a start date and an end date. A system runs continuously, generates data, and improves over time. Everything in this guide is oriented toward building the latter.</p>

      <p>Before you pick a channel or build a landing page, answer three questions in writing:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Who is your target lead?</strong> Not "everyone" — a specific type of person with a specific problem.</li>
        <li><strong>What problem does your product or service solve for them?</strong> Not your features — the outcome they want.</li>
        <li><strong>What is the minimum value exchange you can offer to earn their email address?</strong> What would they find useful enough to hand over their contact information for?</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Once you can answer those three questions clearly, the technical side of lead generation becomes straightforward. The tools — landing page builders, email marketing platforms, traffic sources — are interchangeable. The strategy underneath them is not.</p>

      <div class="callout info">
        <strong>One channel rule:</strong> Commit to mastering one lead generation channel before adding a second. Most beginners who fail do so not because they chose the wrong channel, but because they spread across three or four and gave none of them enough time or volume to produce usable data.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="section-2">
      <h2>2. Define who you want to reach (ICP basics)</h2>

      <p>In lead generation, the term for your ideal target is ICP — Ideal Customer Profile. For beginners, the concept is straightforward: instead of trying to attract everyone, describe one specific type of person in enough detail that you can write directly to them.</p>

      <p>A beginner's ICP does not need to be a formal document. It needs four pieces of information:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Who are they?</strong> — Job title, stage of life, type of business, or situation (e.g., "stay-at-home parent looking for income", "small business owner with fewer than five employees", "person who just left a corporate job")</li>
        <li><strong>What problem are they trying to solve?</strong> — Be specific. "Wants to make money" is too broad. "Wants to replace their £1,800/month salary from home without commuting" is actionable.</li>
        <li><strong>Where do they go to look for solutions?</strong> — Google? Facebook groups? YouTube? LinkedIn? Reddit? Specific newsletters? Your answer directly determines which channel to use in Step 3.</li>
        <li><strong>What would make them trust a source enough to give their email address?</strong> — A checklist? A short guide? A free course? A tool or template? A community invitation?</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Example ICP for an affiliate marketer:</strong> "People searching Google or YouTube for 'how to start affiliate marketing' — complete beginners, no technical background, want a practical starting point, would exchange their email for a step-by-step checklist showing how to earn their first commission."</p>

      <p>This ICP drives every decision that follows: which platform to appear on, what to put on the landing page, what lead magnet to create, and how to write the nurture emails. Without it, you are guessing. With it, every decision has a test: "Does this serve my ICP or not?"</p>

      <p>For affiliate marketers specifically, your ICP is often a version of yourself a few months or years ago — someone at the beginning of the journey you have already taken. That makes it one of the most intuitive ICPs to serve effectively.</p>
    </section>

