    <section id="section-4">
      <h2>4. Build your first lead capture system</h2>

      <p>Traffic without a capture mechanism produces no leads. Once you have a channel generating attention, you need a system to convert that attention into email addresses. The minimum viable lead capture system has three components.</p>

      <h3>Component 1 — The lead magnet</h3>

      <p>A lead magnet is something valuable enough that your target person will exchange their email address for it. It is not a newsletter signup prompt. It is not a vague "join my community." It is a specific, instantly useful resource that solves one concrete problem your ICP has right now.</p>

      <p>The most effective beginner lead magnet formats:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>A checklist</strong> — "The 10-step checklist for [specific task]." Fast to consume, easy to create, and concrete enough to feel immediately valuable. Example: "The 7-step affiliate setup checklist — from link to first commission."</li>
        <li><strong>A short how-to guide</strong> — A 3–5 page PDF walking through a single process step by step. More effort to create but higher perceived value than a checklist.</li>
        <li><strong>A free email course</strong> — A 3–7 day sequence delivered automatically, teaching one skill. This doubles as the beginning of your nurture sequence (Step 5).</li>
        <li><strong>A template or swipe file</strong> — A copy-and-paste resource — email templates, social post templates, script frameworks — that saves the recipient time immediately.</li>
        <li><strong>A free mini-training or video</strong> — A 10–20 minute recorded walkthrough of a process. Higher production effort, higher trust return.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout warn">
        <strong>The specificity test:</strong> Replace your lead magnet title with "a generic overview of my topic." If the result is the same description, your lead magnet is not specific enough. "Everything about affiliate marketing" is too broad. "How to set up your first OLSP affiliate link in 30 minutes — step by step" is specific enough to earn an email address from the right person.
      </div>

      <h3>Component 2 — The landing page</h3>

      <p>A landing page is a single-purpose page with one job: describe the lead magnet clearly and present the email capture form. No navigation menu. No links to other pages. No content that might distract the visitor from completing the form.</p>

      <p>The standard structure that converts:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Headline</strong> — what they get, in specific terms ("Get the free 7-step checklist")</li>
        <li><strong>Sub-headline or brief body</strong> — why it matters to them specifically (one or two sentences connecting the resource to their situation)</li>
        <li><strong>Bullet points</strong> — three to five specific things they will be able to do or know after downloading it</li>
        <li><strong>Form</strong> — first name + email address only. Every extra field reduces conversion rate.</li>
        <li><strong>Button</strong> — a specific action word. "Send me the checklist" or "Get instant access" outperforms "Submit" or "Sign up."</li>
      </ol>

      <p>Free and low-cost tools for beginners: Carrd (free tier), Systeme.io (free tier), ConvertKit landing pages (free with their email plan), or a simple page in Notion shared publicly. You do not need to spend money on a landing page builder to get your first 100 leads.</p>

      <h3>Component 3 — The email marketing platform</h3>

      <p>Your landing page form connects to an email marketing platform that stores subscriber data and delivers automated sequences. For beginners with lists under 1,000 subscribers, the free tiers of these platforms are sufficient:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>ConvertKit (Kit)</strong> — Best for content creators and affiliate marketers. Visual automation builder, clean interface, strong deliverability.</li>
        <li><strong>MailerLite</strong> — Best for simplicity. Free up to 1,000 subscribers, includes landing pages and automation.</li>
        <li><strong>Mailchimp</strong> — Widely used, free up to 500 subscribers. More complex interface, adequate for starting out.</li>
        <li><strong>Systeme.io</strong> — Free tier includes email marketing, funnels, and landing pages in one tool — a practical all-in-one option for affiliate marketers.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>All four integrate with standard landing page tools. Connect your landing page form to your platform, set up a confirmation email, and your capture system is functional.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="section-5">
      <h2>5. Set up your first nurture sequence</h2>

      <p>This is the step that most beginners skip. It is also the primary reason 79% of leads never convert, according to MarketingSherpa. When someone gives you their email address, they are signalling interest — not readiness to buy. Your job in the following days is to build enough trust and relevance that, when they are ready to act, you are the option they choose.</p>

      <p>A beginner's nurture sequence does not need to be complex. Five to seven emails, delivered automatically over two weeks, accomplishes what most beginners need at this stage.</p>

      <ul class="step-list">
        <li>
          <div>
            <strong>Email 1 — Immediate (deliver the lead magnet)</strong>
            Deliver what you promised, exactly as promised. Include a brief personal introduction — one paragraph, not a biography. End with a forward-looking line about what is coming next in the sequence.
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div>
            <strong>Email 2 — Day 2 (one practical tip)</strong>
            Share a single, immediately useful tip related to the problem your ICP is trying to solve. Not a list of ten tips — one. Specific beats comprehensive at this stage of the relationship.
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div>
            <strong>Email 3 — Day 4 (a story or example)</strong>
            A short case study, personal story, or before-and-after example that illustrates the transformation your product or approach enables. Stories build trust faster than facts alone. Keep it under 300 words.
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div>
            <strong>Email 4 — Day 6 (address the biggest objection)</strong>
            Every ICP has a predictable hesitation before taking the next step. Name it directly and address it honestly. "You might be wondering whether [X] works if [common concern]..." This email does more to build credibility than almost anything else in the sequence.
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div>
            <strong>Email 5 — Day 9 (the offer)</strong>
            Make a specific recommendation or offer — your product, your affiliate link, a booking link for a consultation. This is the first time you explicitly ask for something. It should feel natural by now, not abrupt, because the previous four emails have established that you are on the reader's side.
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div>
            <strong>Email 6 — Day 12 (follow-up with social proof)</strong>
            A short testimonial, result, or case study that reinforces the offer. Address a specific objection you anticipate from people who read Email 5 but did not act.
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div>
            <strong>Email 7 — Day 14 (close or re-engage)</strong>
            A final email that either re-engages inactive subscribers ("You haven't heard from me since...") or provides a final, genuine reason to take the next step. After this email, subscribers who have not engaged move to a low-frequency segment rather than continuing to receive the same sequence.
          </div>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout info">
        <strong>The value-first principle:</strong> The sequence above delivers four emails of value before making an offer. This pattern — provide, provide, provide, ask — consistently outperforms leading with a promotion. Companies that use structured lead nurturing generate 50% more sales-ready leads at 33% lower cost than those that do not (Annuitas Group / Demand Gen Report). The investment is five to seven well-written emails. The payoff compounds over every lead that enters your system from this point forward.
      </div>

