    <section id="section-6">
      <h2>6. Track three numbers (and ignore the rest)</h2>

      <p>Beginners do not need a full analytics stack. They need three numbers that reveal whether each component of the system is working.</p>

      <h3>Landing page conversion rate</h3>
      <p>The percentage of visitors who become email subscribers. Calculated as: (Leads ÷ Visitors) × 100. A well-matched lead magnet with clear copy typically converts 20–40% of visitors. Below 10% signals a problem with either the offer, the audience targeting, or the copy. Start troubleshooting with the headline — it has the largest single impact on conversion rate.</p>

      <h3>Email open rate</h3>
      <p>The percentage of subscribers who open each email. Industry averages range from 20–35% depending on niche and list quality. Below 15% consistently suggests a problem with subject lines, sender name recognition, or list quality (too many unengaged addresses). Use your own name as the sender rather than your brand name — it reliably improves open rates for small lists.</p>

      <h3>Cost per lead (if using paid traffic)</h3>
      <p>Total ad spend divided by total leads captured. This is your primary efficiency metric. If it exceeds the value of a lead to your business — either from direct sales or from the lifetime value of your affiliate commissions — you need to either improve your landing page conversion rate or reduce your cost per click. Both are levers. Pull one at a time.</p>

      <p>These three numbers tell you exactly where to focus improvement effort. Everything else — follower counts, email list size, impressions, social media engagement — is context, not signal. If your landing page converts at 30%, your email open rate is 28%, and your cost per lead is below what a lead is worth to you, your system is working. Scale it.</p>
    </section>

