    <section id="section-8">
      <h2>8. Common beginner mistakes</h2>

      <p>Following the steps above in the right order matters more than following them perfectly. Most lead generation failures come from one of five predictable mistakes — all of which are avoidable.</p>

      <h3>Mistake 1: No clear ICP</h3>
      <p>Targeting everyone means resonating with no one. Landing pages written for a specific, well-defined person consistently convert at higher rates than generic pages aimed at a broad audience. Even a rough ICP — one paragraph describing who you are trying to reach and why they would care about your lead magnet — dramatically improves every downstream decision.</p>

      <h3>Mistake 2: Skipping the nurture sequence</h3>
      <p>Collecting email addresses and then sending periodic promotional emails is not lead generation — it is list building with no follow-through. Seventy-nine percent of leads never convert to sales, and the primary reason is lack of structured follow-up. The nurture sequence is where the relationship is built and, eventually, where the sale is made. It is not optional.</p>

      <h3>Mistake 3: Changing channels too quickly</h3>
      <p>Most channels require 30–90 days of consistent effort before you have enough data to evaluate them fairly. A landing page that has received 30 visitors has not been tested. A social media presence that has been active for one week has not been given a chance. Beginners often abandon a channel after seeing no results in the first week — before the channel has had the time or volume to perform.</p>

      <h3>Mistake 4: Building the wrong lead magnet</h3>
      <p>A lead magnet solves a specific, immediate problem — it is not a general overview of your industry. Test your lead magnet title against this question: would my ICP describe this as "exactly what I need right now"? If not, make it more specific. "A guide to affiliate marketing" is too broad. "How to earn your first $5 affiliate commission in 48 hours — step-by-step" targets a specific outcome at a specific moment in the reader's journey.</p>

      <h3>Mistake 5: Measuring the wrong things</h3>
      <p>Social media follower counts, email list size, and page view totals are lagging indicators. They tell you what happened. The three numbers from Step 6 — landing page conversion rate, email open rate, cost per lead — are leading indicators. They tell you what to fix before you scale. Beginners who optimise for follower counts often build audiences that never become leads. Beginners who optimise for conversion rate build systems that compound.</p>
    </section>

